      <p>AI can't make decisions for us, but it can accelerate our decision making — and the best decisions emerge from collaboration, not isolation.</p>

      <p><em>I got pretty far on writing this before bringing in my agent to help sort my thoughts. Can you tell where my writing ends and my agent's begins?</em></p>

      <!-- Epilogue -->
      <aside class="rounded-xl border border-scale/20 bg-scale/5 px-6 py-5 my-8">
        <p class="!mb-2 !text-base"><strong class="text-bone">Epilogue — March 2026</strong></p>
        <p class="!mb-0 !text-sm text-mist">
          Six weeks after writing this, I hit every wall I predicted — and some I didn't. Identity drift, context amnesia, rule bloat, fighting the architecture instead of building on it. The collaboration loop I described here was real, but the infrastructure underneath wasn't ready for it. That's what led to <a href="/">Ouroboros</a>: an agent harness designed from scratch around the idea that your agent is a teammate, not a tool — and that the planning artifacts, the shared memory, the collaborative process described in this essay should be first-class primitives, not afterthoughts.
        </p>
